sentences: Starting in Los Angeles at Autumn Records in the 1960s, he later founded the San Francisco studio Golden State Recorders, trade school College for Recording Arts and audiophile record label Sonic Arts.
Leo de Gar Kulka was born in 1921 in Brno, Czechoslovakia.
After studying engineering, Kulka moved to Los Angeles in 1938.
In 1957 he founded International Sound, one of the first multitrack facilities in Hollywood.
In 1964 Kulka moved to San Francisco and founded Golden State Recorders, one of the largest recording studios in northern California.
In 1974 he founded the College for Recording Arts, dedicated to training aspiring music industry employees in all aspects of the industry.
In 1994 he closed the College for Recording Arts, instead devoting his time to analog and digital mastering, and the restoration of vintage sound recordings.
As a member of the Audio Engineering Society since 1959, he first served in Los Angeles, and then as chairman of the San Francisco Section for multiple terms.
He was chairman of the 93rd Convention that was held over October from the 1st to 4th San Francisco in 1992.
In 1993 Kulka was elected treasurer and chairman of the Finance Committee.
In 1995 he was awarded with an AES Fellowship Award for his contributions to education and sound recording practices.
Leo De Gar Kulka died on March 17, 1998, aged 77.

sentences: Leo De Gar Kulka (February 17, 1921 – March 17, 1998) was a Czech-born American record producer, recording engineer and educator.

Starting in Los Angeles at Autumn Records in the 1960s, he later founded the San Francisco studio Golden State Recorders, trade school College for Recording Arts and audiophile record label Sonic Arts.
The studio, located on Sunset at Western, later became Sunwest.
